        I wake sore — every muscle announcing itself loudly: legs, back, shoulders. Everything aches in that deep way that comes from using body parts in new ways.

        Buddy said, "Told you."

        I said, "Not helpful, Buddy."

        Buddy said, "Microtrauma and repair — your muscles are adapting beautifully."

        Leafwhisper's leaves rustled nearby.

        Leafwhisper said, "Good morning! How are you feeling? I predicted soreness, which I see was accurate — very normal adaptation process. The discomfort should ease significantly once you start moving — muscles warm up and the stiffness reduces." 

        I groaned, "Coffee — do plants have coffee?"

        Leafwhisper said, "Sadly no — but movement will help, I promise — and we have a slightly shorter distance today to accommodate the adaptation period: only about twenty kilometers, which should feel more manageable." 

        Rootwalker appeared with water and mushroom paste for breakfast.

        The paste tasted exactly like yesterday: gray, earthy, functional.

        Leafwhisper was right — once I start moving the soreness eases into a dull background ache rather than sharp pain.

        The walking feels different today — less foreign, my body remembering the rhythm.

        Step, step, step.

        Follow Rootwalker's steady pace — half-listen to Leafwhisper's commentary and let Scout explore.

        The forest is changing. Deeper in, different species dominate. The canopy grows denser, filtering light into green-gold patterns. Plants I don't recognize cluster along the path — some flowering in bizarre fractal geometries, others moving in slow, deliberate ways that make me wonder if they're watching.

        Leafwhisper said, "— and these are Spiral-types! Fascinating adaptation — they process information through rotational growth patterns — very different cognitive architecture from linear-processing species — they experience time in layers rather than sequences, which makes communication challenging but wonderfully interesting." 

        I said, "Wait — time in layers?"

        Leafwhisper said, "Yes! Instead of experiencing moments consecutively they perceive multiple timeframes simultaneously — past, present, future as concurrent states — it's quite disorienting to interact with if you're used to linear causality." 

        Rootwalker confirmed, "Confusing."

        Leafwhisper rustled agreement.

        Leafwhisper said, "Very — but they're excellent at pattern recognition across long timescales — very useful for ecological planning." 

        I try to imagine experiencing time as layers instead of a sequence — and fail completely.

        Scout bounces ahead to investigate a cluster of luminescent mushrooms. The little plant seems endlessly curious about new species.

        I asked, "Does Scout understand what they're encountering? Like, can plants tell what other plants are thinking?"
      </text>
