        Leafwhisper's leaves shimmered. Leafwhisper said, "Wonderful question! It varies tremendously by species! Scout uses primarily physical perception — bounce patterns, surface texture, chemical signatures — which gives them information about other organisms but not direct thought-sharing. Some species, like Holloway back at the facility, can access network communication directly through underground connections, sharing actual information and coordination. Others communicate through touch, like those vines you met, conveying emotions and intentions but not complex language. It's a spectrum of connection depth!"

        I asked, "So you can't just automatically understand every plant you meet?"

        Leafwhisper replied, "Not at all! Learning human language was revolutionary precisely because it gave us a common communication framework across very different cognitive types. Before that, coordination happened through slow chemical signaling and shared network protocols, much less efficient for individual conversation —"

        Rootwalker interjected, "Worked fine for a long time."

        Leafwhisper said, "Well yes! It worked — I'm not saying it didn't work — just that verbal language added new capabilities, expanded what was possible in terms of cross-species coordination and individual expression —"

        Rootwalker observed, "More talking."

        I laugh despite my sore muscles. I say, "You two really do balance each other out."

        Leafwhisper agreed happily, "Complementary! Rootwalker thinks I talk too much — which is fair criticism honestly, and I think Rootwalker should explain reasoning more often — which is also fair from their perspective! Different communication needs, both valid —"

        Rootwalker replied, "True. Works fine."

        They walked through a section where massive trees had grown so close their trunks fused, creating living arches over the path. The root systems below were completely merged — impossible to tell where one organism ended and another began.

        I asked, "Is that what your society is like? All merged together?"

        Leafwhisper considered this. Leafwhisper said, "Physically yes, through root and fungal networks we share resources and information. But mentally and experientially? We're individuals. The HR manuals helped us understand that distinction actually — helped us see that sharing space and resources didn't mean lacking individual identity. Very clarifying framework, even if some applications were absurd!"

        I say, "Morning wellness checks."

        Leafwhisper said, "Exactly! The bureaucratic procedures were clearly designed for beings who don't naturally coordinate through shared networks, so applying them literally to us was unnecessarily redundant, but the underlying concepts about individual needs and identity were genuinely useful —"

        Rootwalker said suddenly, "Question."

        They'd reached another rest stop. I haven't even noticed the kilometers passing. My body has found the rhythm. I sit gratefully anyway.

        Scout rolled over immediately, settling against my leg. The little plant was learning rest stop patterns too.
      </text>
