        Leafwhisper observes, "You're doing much better today—less visible fatigue, more efficient movement, exactly as predicted! The human adaptation capacity is remarkable, really—"

        I ask, "How did you end up doing this? Being guides?"

        Leafwhisper brightens and says, "Oh! I've always been mobile—developed the stem and leaf structure naturally during growth, and I loved exploring different territories, so guiding seemed like a perfect role—combining navigation with meeting new beings and sharing information—"

        Rootwalker says simply, "Like walking—still like walking."

        Leafwhisper continues, "Yes—Rootwalker's reasoning is more direct. They enjoy terrain navigation and found purpose in helping travelers—very straightforward motivations—"

        I drink water and watch the forest breathe around us. Because it does breathe—not just individual plants but the whole system, expanding and contracting in slow rhythm. Sharing resources. Communicating. Living as both individuals and collective.

        It is beautiful in a way that makes my chest tight.

        I say quietly, "I miss trees. Back home. But they weren't like this. They were just... trees. Individual plants competing for light and water."

        Rootwalker observes, "Lonely way to live."

        Leafwhisper replies, "It must have been! Though Earth forests did have fungal networks too—early human researchers just didn't recognize the communication happening underground—thought of trees as isolated entities when really they were sharing resources and information all along, just without individual language to make it obvious—"

        I ask, "So Earth forests were networks too?"

        Leafwhisper replies, "Less sophisticated than here—less intentional coordination; but yes! The capacity exists in forest ecosystems generally—we've just developed it further, made it more conscious and communicative—"

        Rootwalker says, "Time."

        I stand. Still sore, but manageable. The rhythm called.

        They walked.

        The afternoon passed in questions and answers—Leafwhisper explaining plant society structures, territorial networks, how different species contributed different capabilities, why some plants stayed rooted while others developed mobility, what it felt like to photosynthesize, whether mushrooms counted as plants or their own category.

        Rootwalker contributed occasional one-word clarifications or corrections.

        Scout continued exploring, bringing back chemical signatures from interesting discoveries.

        And I walk, learning to see the forest not as backdrop but as society—complex, interconnected, beautiful.

        When they reached the second rest shelter that evening, I feel tired but strong—twenty kilometers—done.

        Leafwhisper says while synthesizing dinner, "Tomorrow's the last day in Territory One—we'll reach the boundary mid-afternoon, transfer you to Territory Two guides, and then Rootwalker and I head back home—"

        ¶

        Something twisted in my chest.

        I say, "Already?"
